Brief Description: Political election programs split into "quasi-sentences," each annotated with one of 56 standard policy semantic codes (e.g., Welfare Expansion, Market Regulation).
QA Method: Rigorous human coder training + Inter-coder reliability tests (Krippendorff’s Alpha provided in docs).
Comments: It contains rich semantic codes (e.g., "Traditional Morality: Negative"), not just dates/regions. Perfect for S1 alignment.

Brief Description: Verbatim transcripts from Federal Reserve meetings. Sentences are annotated for "Hawkish" (tightening) vs "Dovish" (easing) stance and opinionatedness.
QA Method: Expert annotation (PhD economists) vs. LLM baseline.
Comments: Dataset explicitly shows a gap: Human Accuracy (0.89) >> LLM (0.61). We can use LIWC/Luke to investigate if "high complexity/low emotion" language causes this alignment failure.
